    <text>
        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>St Thomas</placeName> <date>June 4 1853</date></p>
			<p><addressee>Reverend Mr Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p><placeName>Phia</placeName></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">I have received all<lb/> your letters &#38; would have long<lb/> since replied but for the<lb/> large amount of anxiety &#38;<lb/> unhappiness produced by the<lb/> crisis &#38; its effects which has been<lb/> so destructive over the world&#44;<lb/> besides I have been very dissat<lb/>isfied with the manner you<lb/> have lately conducted the<lb/> Occident&#44; you have permitted<lb/> &#38; published the most <sic>scurilous</sic></p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>articles to be inserted that<lb/> was positively a disgrace to<lb/> any respectable party&#44; witness<lb/> the article on <persName>Mr Wise</persName> of<lb/> <placeName><sic>Cincinati</sic></placeName>&#44; I declare I was<lb/> shocked at reading it &#38; then<lb/> it appears that each of our<lb/> ministers in <placeName>Ama.</placeName> Mention<lb/> his best endeavors to bring his<lb/> fellow into contempt &#38; de<add>&#63;</add>&#44;<lb/> why is this&#44; when will our<lb/> pretended wise men see that in<lb/> endeavoring to humble their<lb/> fellow&#44; they are using every effort<lb/> to disgust their laymen. I<lb/> confess that I would rather be<lb/> without any ministry than be</p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p>disgraced by such a one as<lb/> your pages exhibit&#8212;<add>&#63;</add> <persName>Mr<lb/> Leeser</persName> put a stop to the<lb/> scandal you publish to the<lb/> world.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I enclose the Bank of St Thomas<lb/> Bill No 9717 on <persName>J C Whitmore</persName> <placeName>New York</placeName> for &#36;23.53&#59; for the following&#59;<lb/> received from this congregation<lb/> for advertisements omitted last<lb/> remittance &#36;6&#8212;<lb/> one year subscription<lb/> to Occident for <date>1857</date> for<lb/> 9<add>&#63;</add> subscribers&#160;&#160;9&#8212;<lb/> one year for two for <date>1858</date> 6.&#8212;<lb/> received from <persName>Piza</persName> for<lb/> your a&#47;c&#160;&#160;3<lb/> Bill &#36;23.53 &#36;24&#8212;<lb/> premium .47<lb/> &#36;24&#8212;</p>
		<pb n="4"/>
			<p>which balances our account.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">My wife joins with kind<lb/> regardes &#38; to <persName>Mr. &#38; Mrs Florence</persName><lb/> whom we hope are in the<lb/> enjoyment of health</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">Yours truly</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)"><persName role="author">A. Wolff</persName></p>
			<p>You will remark that <sic>their</sic><lb/> is one Subscriber less than<lb/> last year&#44; a party who left<lb/> the <placeName>Island</placeName>.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">In referring to my memo of<lb/> after the Bill was drawn I find<lb/> I <sic>creditted</sic> you with &#36;&#8212;40&#47;100 less<lb/> on the sum recd from the Synagogue<lb/> authorities&#44; which will be remembered<lb/> the next remittance</p>
          
        </body>
